Project : AI-Driven Temperature Analysis for Better Educational Environments in Tanzania

Project Goal : Develop a predictive model using AI, satellite imagery / remote sensing data, and classroom characteristics (e.g., ceiling boards). that can estimate indoor classroom temperatures.

1.3. Define number of past and future timepoints for data preparation

In[33]:
# Define the number of past and future timepoints
#===========================================================================================================================
oneday_tps    = 24     # 1hr*24 = 1 day
n_past_days   = 5     # number of previous days data to be considered to predict temperature at next timepoints
n_future_days = 3      # number of future days data to be predicted

n_past_tps    = int(n_past_days*oneday_tps)    # number of previous time points data to be used, to predict the value for the next time point.
n_future_tps  = int(n_future_days*oneday_tps)     # Number of timepoints we want to forecast into the future based on the past timepoints
In[34]:
print(n_past_tps, n_future_tps)

3. Data Preparation for LSTM model

3.1 Creating Training, Validation and Testing sets

  • here previous no_prev_timepoints (the number of previous timepoints data to use) are used to predict the value for the next timepoint.
  • no_prev_timepoints are required before the 1st date in the validation and test dataset.
  • Accordingly, create input data for validation prediciton and testing prediction, index starting from the date no_prev_timepoints days before the first date in the validation or test dataset.
In[54]:
# number of previous time points data to be used, to predict the value for the next time point.
no_prev_timepoints = n_past_tps     
train_percent = 0.80       # percentage of data for training
# Note : remaining percentage will be used for validation
#===========================================================================================================
# copy the selected columns in to a dataframe
df = df_initial[['Avg_indoor_temp(hourly)','temperature_2m','relative_humidity_2m', 
                 'direct_normal_irradiance','shortwave_radiation', 'wind_speed_10m', 
                 'cloud_cover','NDVI(monthly)', 'NDWI(monthly)']].values

# copy the date column which will be used later for plotting
df_date = df_initial['Date']
#============================================================================================================

# split the data in to training & validation 
train_split = int(len(df)*train_percent)

train_set = df[:train_split]      # training dataset
val_set   = df[train_split:]      # validation dataset

val_set_4generator  = df[train_split-no_prev_timepoints:]   # only for timeseries generator, validation dataset 

#=============================================================================================================
date_train = df_initial['Date'][:train_split]          # used for plotting. Dates corresponding to training data
date_val = df_initial['Date'][train_split:]   

timepoint_train = df_initial['Timepoint'][:train_split]          # used for plotting. Dates corresponding to training data
timepoint_val = df_initial['Timepoint'][train_split:]   

date_val_4generator  = df_initial['Date'][train_split-no_prev_timepoints:]   # used for plotting. Dates corresponding to validation data
timepoint_val_4generator  = df_initial['Timepoint'][train_split-no_prev_timepoints:]   # used for plotting. Dates corresponding to validation data

#=============================================================================================================
print("Full dataset length                  : ", len(df))
print("Training set length                  : ", len(train_set))
print("Validation set length                : ", len(val_set))

print("no_prev_timepoints                   : ", no_prev_timepoints)
print("Validation set length (for generator): ", len(val_set_4generator))
print(len(train_set)+len(val_set))

3.4. Define TimeseriesGenerator for training, validation and testing sets

  • here previous no_prev_timepoints (the number of previous timepoints data to use) are used to predict the value for the next timepoint.
  • no_prev_timepoints are required before the 1st date in the validation and test dataset.

In[76]:
#=========================================================================================
# 1. Training dataset : train_set_scaled
#=========================================================================================
df = train_set_scaled

#As required for LSTM networks, we require to reshape an input data into (number of samples X timesteps X number of features)

trainX = []  # list to store input features
trainY = []  # list to store target label

# Reformat input data into a shape: (n_samples x timesteps x n_features)
for i in range(n_past_tps, len(df) - n_future_tps +1):
    trainX.append(df[i - n_past_tps:i, 0:df.shape[1]])
    trainY.append(df[i :i + n_future_tps, 0])           # target column is in 0th column (Tair)

trainX, trainY = np.array(trainX), np.array(trainY)

print("Full dataset length : ", len(df))
print("trainX shape        :", trainX.shape)
print("trainY shape        :", trainY.shape)

4. Build RNN - LSTM Model

4.1. Create LSTM Model

In[86]:
num_features = train_set_scaled.shape[1]
#===========================================================================
#1st LSTM layer
# Note : if the activation function is "relu" then will get the following 
# WARNING:tensorflow:Layer LSTM_1 will not use cuDNN kernels since it doesn't meet the criteria.

with tf.device('/device:GPU:0'):
    model = Sequential() 

    #model.add(GaussianNoise(0.1, input_shape = (no_prev_timepoints, num_features)))
    #model.add(LSTM(units=128, return_sequences=False, name='LSTM_1'))
    model.add(LSTM(units=128, input_shape = (no_prev_timepoints, num_features), return_sequences=True, name='LSTM_1'))
    
    model.add(LSTM(units=128, name='LSTM_2'))
    
    # Output layer
    model.add(Dense(trainY.shape[1], name='Output'))

model.summary()
